One question raised in the literature regarding immune properties of breastmilk is which immune factors of breastmilk are influenced by maternal health and/or maternal psychosocial well-being. Current research describes the relationships between maternal characteristics and the immunological properties of breastmilk and explores interventions to improve the immune factors of breastmilk (see Table 1
). A potential guiding framework for furthering our understanding of the relationship between maternal psychosocial characteristics and breastmilk immune factors is a conceptual model based on Lazarus and Folkman’s (1984) stress and coping model (see Figure 1
). The stress in the model derives from both the physical and the psychosocial experience of becoming the mother of a preterm infant, which includes stressors not typical for all new mothers. Mothers of hospitalized preterm infants must cope with physical separation from their infant, concerns over infant health, and provision of breastmilk using a mechanical pump, until the neonate can be successfully placed at the breast. The process of coping involves using realistic and flexible thoughts and actions to solve problems that impact the perceived stress of the lactating preterm mother, which then generates stress-related immune responses in the breastmilk (Lazarus & Folkman, 1984; Witek-Janusek & Mathews, 2000).
